{
  "texts": [
    "This behavior stems from the fundamental training objective of LLMs, which is to predict the most probable sequence of tokens given the input source code.",
    "The model itself lacks an independent, formal understanding of the program's intended specification; it learns patterns directly from the given code.",
    "Consequently, if the provided code contains a bug, the LLM is likely to treat this faulty logic as intended behavior and generate tests that confirm it [66].",
    "This is evidenced in empirical studies showing that tests generated from incorrect code pass at a significantly higher rate on the same incorrect code, effectively cementing the error [66].",
    "Empirical analysis also reports that despite high coverage, test suites are untrustworthy and exhibit high false positives [176]."
  ]
}